Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.

### Instruction:
what does this command do: ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com

### Response:

This command allows you to connect to an Amazon EC2 instance using SSH (Secure Shell) protocol. Here's a breakdown of the different parts of this command:
1. "ssh -i" specifies that we will use a private key file named "UserKey.pem". This is typically stored in your home directory on the local machine where you are running the command.
2. "-C" tells SSH to not create any new windows when connecting, which helps prevent accidental login screens from appearing on other devices.
3. "-L 25900:localhost:5900" specifies that we will forward port 25900 on the local machine to port 5900 on the remote server running at "ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com". This allows us to access a service that is only available on the remote server through our local machine.
4. Finally, we specify the username and hostname of the EC2 instance in the command: "user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com".
